'Suddenly, for whatever reason, Sagittarius A* is eating a lot more,' said MIT Kavli research scientist Michael Nowak. 'One theory is that every so often, an asteroid gets close to the black hole, the black hole stretches and rips it to pieces, and eats the material and turns it into radiation, so you see these big flares.'

Dr Nowak told MITnews that he suspects such flare-ups occur more frequently than scientists had previously thought and the team have now reserved more than a month on Chandra to observe Sagittarius A* in the hopes of detecting more and finding out what is causing them.

Another question the team hopes to investigate is why the black hole gives off so little energy. Dr Baganoff in 2003 calculated that given the amount of gas surrounding it, Sagittarius A* should be a million times brighter.

His findings suggested that the black hole is actually throwing away most of the matter that floats into its gravitational pull - the physics of which remains a puzzle that could explain the history of our galaxy.

